description: I led an 82 man NATO Coalition team as Chief CJ3 (essentially OC Ops/Airfield Manager) to Commander, Kandahar Airfield (KAF) (COMKAF). With almost 400 aircraft permanently based there, KAF is the World's busiest single runway airfield, Afghanistan's busiest heliport and ISAF's principal strategic air base. These aircraft are a unique combination of military and civilian fixed wing (Fast jet CAS, C4ISR, transport, commercial and RPA/UAS) and rotary wing assets. During my tenure, operations reached unprecedented levels of 800 fixed wing sorties alone per day with fixed and rotary movements combining to produce over 40 000 per month (2012 saw 473 000 movements at KAF. In comparison, London Gatwick experienced 240 000 movements in 2011-12 with the luxury of an alternative runway). These record levels were achieved despite extensive essential repairs to taxiways and both thresholds of KAF's runway during my tour. I led Coalition military and contractor personnel in coordinating these contracts (worth approximately £20M) with operations to ensure that impact to ISAF capacity and Afghan commercial interests was minimised. This involved liaison with tenant NATO and Afghan military units, ISAF Joint Command, CAOC, contractors as well as the Afghan Ministry of Transport and Civil Aviation. Although CJ3 focused, I became heavily involved in advising IJC and NATO JFC Brunssum in transition planning, notably regarding future ISR posture, basing options and the transfer of KAF facilities to Afghan control. Aligned to this, I assisted in the mentoring of the Afghan Airport Manager of the civilian terminal to develop the nascent commercial potential of this facility. Other responsibilities involved the staffing of Coalition basing requests and the recovery of airfield operations following insurgent rocket and suicide attacks.

description: I acted as the principal ISTAR staff officer within the J3 (Current Operations) Division of PJHQ. Primary duties involved the provision of specialist Maritime, Land and Air ISTAR advice to star rank, HM Government, MoD and single service organizations, campaign planning and management of assets. Key activities included coordination and operational level tasking of the following: Afghanistan. - Base ISTAR (notably CORTEZ and aerostats). - Force Protection/Counter Threat (including Unattended Ground Sensors and Counter Improvised Explosive Device). - UAS/RPAS capabilities and integration (H450, Watchkeeper, Desert Hawk 3, Predator and Reaper). - Air C2ISR (Nimrod R1, Sentinel R1, Sea King ASaC7, E-3D, GR4 RAPTOR/Litening III). - SF capabilities. - Operational trials. - Staffing of Urgent Operational Requirements (UOR). Specific ISR capabilities covered were EO/IR including FMV, SAR/GMTI, LIDAR, SIGINT of all types and Hyper/multi spectral intelligence (HSI/MSI) techniques. Although ‘collection’ centric, an underlying aspect of my role was in reinforcing the need for such capabilities to be ‘exploitation led’. Accordingly, I worked closely with the J2 (Intelligence) Division, Other Government Departments and coalition partners regarding related Processing, Exploitation and Dissemination (PED) capabilities such as the Distributed Common Ground System (DCGS). Libya - Initial campaign planning and deployment tasking of UK Air and Maritime C2ISR assets in support of non-combatant evacuation and subsequent transition to combat operations. - Dynamic apportionment of assets between operational theatres to ensure the optimum enduring posture available. Aside from the above operations I was responsible for UK ISTAR contingency planning and activities in all other theatres commanded by the UK Chief of Joint Operations. This notably included Iraq, the Northern Arabian Gulf and counter terrorism and piracy ops.
